  "signature": "ed25519:7b3e1a9c2d4f6b8e0a2c4d6f8b0e2a4c6d8f0b2e4a6c8d0f2b4e6a8c0d2f4b6e",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 and FDA in-house FEA code both operate under ISO 9001-certified quality management systems with documented V&V test suites. Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes in the ensemble (FDA in-house, Ansys Mechanical, DePuy Synthes internal) are operated under documented software quality management frameworks. Version control, regression testing, and release qualification records are available. Achieved Gradation 3 — formal SQA plan with periodic audits — exceeds the required Gradation 2 for this medium model-risk context."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification through benchmark problems documented in solver theory manuals and supplementary verification reports. Achieved level must equal required level.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical code verification is documented against NAFEMS benchmarks for contact mechanics and large-deformation plasticity. FDA in-house code has been verified against analytic solutions for beam bending and Hertzian contact. Both codes achieve Gradation 2 (verification against standard benchmark problems), meeting the required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating <2% change in QoIs between successive refinements. Richardson extrapolation applied where applicable.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted on the pedicle screw-rod construct model. Three mesh densities were evaluated (coarse ~85k elements, medium ~210k elements, fine ~520k elements). QoI differences between medium and fine meshes were 0.8% for stiffness and 1.3% for yield force, both within the 2% threshold. Richardson extrapolation confirmed GCI < 1.5% for all primary QoIs. Discretization error is adequately controlled at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual norms monitored and reported; iterative convergence criteria tightened until QoI insensitivity demonstrated.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson convergence criteria were set to force residual < 1e-4 and displacement residual < 1e-5. Sensitivity of QoIs to tightening by one order of magnitude showed <0.2% change. Nonlinear contact iterations were monitored for chattering; stabilization energy was confirmed to be <0.5% of total strain energy. Gradation 2 achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented model setup procedures, independent review of boundary conditions, and cross-code comparison to detect operator-induced discrepancies.",
      "rationale": "Model setup was independently reviewed by a second analyst for each of the three codes in the ensemble. Boundary condition application, contact pair definitions, and material assignment were verified against the ASTM F1717 test fixture specification. Cross-code comparison of intermediate outputs (reaction forces at fixture pins, contact pressure distributions) served as an additional check against use error. Gradation 3 achieved, exceeding the required Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection justified by material characterization data; contact formulation validated against known analytic or experimental benchmarks for similar geometries.",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) material behavior is represented by a bilinear isotropic hardening model calibrated to tensile coupon data (n=5 per lot). The augmented Lagrangian contact formulation was selected based on prior validation studies for threaded fastener interfaces. Geometric nonlinearity (large-displacement formulation) is activated given expected deflections exceeding 10% of characteristic length. Model form choices are consistent with published literature for similar pedicle screw FEA studies. Gradation 3 is achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties derived from lot-specific coupon testing; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test articles; uncertainty in inputs propagated to QoI uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and tangent modulus were measured from tensile coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock as the test constructs. CMM measurements of screw geometry (outer diameter, thread pitch, core diameter) were used to parameterize the CAD model. Uncertainty in material inputs was propagated via a 50-sample Latin hypercube study; the resulting QoI uncertainty band was incorporated into the validation metric. Gradation 3 achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples traceable to production lot; dimensional inspection completed; sample size sufficient to characterize experimental variability (N≥5 per condition).",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: N=6, Lab 2: N=5). All constructs were drawn from the same production lot with documented dimensional inspection (CMM, 100% sampling). Inter-laboratory variability was assessed via ANOVA; no statistically significant lab effect was detected (p=0.31 for stiffness). Sample size exceeds minimum for Gradation 3 characterization of experimental scatter."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate COU loading environment; at least two independent load configurations or load levels evaluated to bound model behavior across the intended use space.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted exclusively under the ASTM F1717 standard configuration (35 mm offset, compressive bending, displacement-controlled at 1 mm/min). Only a single test condition was evaluated; alternative load levels or offset distances were not explored. This limits the ability to assess model behavior across the full intended use space, resulting in Gradation 2 achieved against a required Gradation 3. This factor is noted as below the required level and is documented as a known gap in the validation campaign."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters demonstrably equivalent to experimental conditions; any deviations quantified and their effect on QoIs bounded.",
      "rationale": "Fixture geometry, applied displacement rate, and boundary conditions in the FEA model were set to match the ASTM F1717 test configuration. The only deviation is the representation of the UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate: the model uses a homogeneous linear-elastic block calibrated to published indentation data. Sensitivity analysis showed <3% effect on stiffness QoI and <2% effect on yield force QoI from ±20% variation in surrogate modulus. Gradation 2 achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative validation metric (E/uval) computed for all primary QoIs; E/uval < 1.96 required for acceptance; percent difference < 10% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Validation metric E/uval was computed for stiffness (0.84), yield force (1.21), and force at 40 mm (1.07), all below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences were 4.2%, 6.8%, and 5.1% respectively, all within the 10% acceptance bound. Results are consistent across all three codes in the ensemble (max inter-code spread 1.9%). Gradation 3 achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected are directly linked to the clinical failure mode of interest and to the regulatory submission claim.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the primary mechanical endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the clinical risk of screw-rod construct failure leading to loss of spinal fixation. These QoIs are explicitly cited in the 510(k) predicate device comparison and in the FDA guidance on spinal implant testing. Gradation 3 achieved, exceeding the required Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation activities are judged to be sufficiently representative of the COU based on a holistic qualitative assessment of loading mode, device geometry, material system, and regulatory context. No formal graded level is assigned because the breadth of the validation campaign — spanning two independent laboratories, three independent FEA codes, and direct comparison to the regulatory standard test method — provides a qualitative basis for confidence that exceeds what any single gradation descriptor captures. The assessment team consensus is that the validation activities are appropriate and sufficient for the intended regulatory use.",
      "rationale": "The validation campaign directly replicates the ASTM F1717 regulatory standard test that will be cited in the 510(k) submission. The same screw geometry, rod diameter, rod material, and polyaxial head design used in the submission are represented in both the FEA models and the physical test constructs. Two independent laboratories and three independent FEA codes participated, providing strong cross-verification of results. The loading mode (compression-bending) is the most clinically relevant failure mode for posterior spinal fixation systems. The validation team conducted a comprehensive qualitative assessment of relevance across all dimensions — geometric fidelity, loading fidelity, material fidelity, and regulatory alignment — and concluded that the validation activities are highly relevant to the COU. This factor has been assessed through expert judgment and documented consensus rather than through assignment of a formal required or achieved gradation level, as the multi-code, multi-laboratory design of the campaign renders single-axis grading an oversimplification of the actual evidence base."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. One factor (Test conditions) achieves Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3, reflecting the single-condition ASTM F1717 test design; this gap is accepted given the regulatory standardization of the test method and the absence of a predicate requiring multi-condition validation for this device class. Quantitative validation metrics (E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs; percent differences < 10%) are satisfied across all three FEA codes in the ensemble. The overall credibility evidence is sufficient to support the intended regulatory use of the FEA modeling framework for this COU. Decision: Accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
